00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:04.800
﻿Since starting this YouTube channel, I've made&nbsp;
17 maps on different areas of physics, and one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:09.600
thing I've learned is that physics itself is still&nbsp;
incomplete. And this is really annoying because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:14.560
I want to understand things about the universe,&nbsp;
and there's many big mysteries that we just don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:19.920
understand. So this makes me wonder, will we ever&nbsp;
be able to complete physics and have a complete&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:25.360
understanding of the universe? Or is it actually&nbsp;
impossible? So in this video, I'm going to look at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.360 --> 00:00:31.840
some of the biggest mysteries that plague physics&nbsp;
today and try and gauge whether those will be one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:36.880
day solvable, or whether they'll be forever&nbsp;
outside of our reach. And we just have to give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:43.360
up on any hope that will actually ever understand&nbsp;
everything about the universe. So I was thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:48.800
about what you need for a successful theory of&nbsp;
physics. And essentially there's eight things you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:56.000
need to describe. So first you need a description&nbsp;
of space. So 3D space and then time. Then matter.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:00.560
The stuff in that space which is mostly atoms.&nbsp;
And then you need to describe energy which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:06.160
basically how anything happens. So if you describe&nbsp;
how energy moves through matter in space and time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.160 --> 00:01:11.200
that's basically all of what physics does. Okay.&nbsp;
So that's the first four. Now the second four.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:16.800
We've got the four mechanisms of how energy can&nbsp;
flow around. And these are the four fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:21.920
forces. First, gravity, the old apple on the&nbsp;
head. Basically all matter in the universe weakly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.920 --> 00:01:27.920
attracts all other matter. Then electromagnetism.&nbsp;
This is basically everything else that's not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.920 --> 00:01:34.080
gravity. If you zoom in on any process closely&nbsp;
enough, it's governed by what the electrons around&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:40.400
atoms are doing. Mechanical processes, chemical&nbsp;
process, how light works. Electronics. That's all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:45.680
electromagnetism. And finally the nuclear strong&nbsp;
and nuclear weak forces which happened inside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.680 --> 00:01:50.880
the nuclei of atoms. And these are important&nbsp;
in nuclear physics and radioactivity. But we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:55.840
don't experience these day to day. So these are&nbsp;
the eight things that physics needs to explain.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.840 --> 00:02:02.880
And today we can't explain all eight with one&nbsp;
single theory. Okay. So the biggest problem in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:08.880
modern physics is that we don't have a theory&nbsp;
of quantum gravity. To explain what this means,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:13.920
we need to look at my map of physics for&nbsp;
an overview. This was actually my first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:18.960
map I made on this channel. If you're new here,&nbsp;
I've made loads of maps about various subjects,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:23.760
and if you want to get your hands on any of&nbsp;
these, I sell them as posters. The links are at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:29.760
dosmaps.com. I'm about to go on paternity leave.&nbsp;
I'm having my first child. So if any of my work&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:33.920
has been useful to you and you want to help me&nbsp;
out, this is a great way to do that along with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:40.080
my Patreon. So all of the links to all of that are&nbsp;
in the description below. Thank you. But anyway,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:46.400
the map of physics: physics basically boils down&nbsp;
into three sections. We've got classical physics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.400 --> 00:02:51.280
relativity, and quantum mechanics. Of the eight&nbsp;
things that physics needs to describe. Classical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:57.680
physics covers these six, but it doesn't really&nbsp;
describe atoms. So we need quantum physics for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:03.600
strong and the weak forces. But classical physics&nbsp;
is really just an approximation for human scale.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:09.680
So the correct description for time and space&nbsp;
is relativity where it split into two parts.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:14.720
Special relativity puts space and time together&nbsp;
into a combined entity called space time. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:20.480
then general relativity describes gravity as&nbsp;
the curvature of that space time. Then at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:26.080
bottom we've got quantum mechanics. And that's&nbsp;
the accurate description of electromagnetism&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.080 --> 00:03:32.320
matter and energy. So all we need to do is join&nbsp;
quantum mechanics and relativity together. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:37.360
then we'd have a theory of everything, a theory&nbsp;
of quantum gravity. Now people have been trying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:42.320
to do this and have managed to jam quantum&nbsp;
mechanics and special relativity together into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:49.600
a theory called quantum field theory. But whenever&nbsp;
anyone has tried putting general relativity and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:55.040
its description of gravity into quantum field&nbsp;
theory, it doesn't work. There's a fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.040 --> 00:04:00.240
incompatibility with the smooth, continuous&nbsp;
nature of space time and the blocky, chunky&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.240 --> 00:04:06.800
nature of quantum mechanics. And if you smash all&nbsp;
the mass together, you end up getting infinities&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.800 --> 00:04:11.760
and paradoxes, and it doesn't work. People have&nbsp;
been trying to do this for over a hundred years,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:16.880
unsuccessfully. So for now, a theory of quantum&nbsp;
gravity is on the other side of the chasm of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:22.080
ignorance, along with other big mysteries like&nbsp;
dark matter and dark energy. Dark matter is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.080 --> 00:04:27.920
basically some form of unknown matter that makes&nbsp;
up 85% of the universe. We know what makes up the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.440
normal matter, and that's described by the&nbsp;
Standard Model of particle physics. But this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:37.600
is only 15% of the universe. We probably won't&nbsp;
need a theory of quantum gravity to explain dark&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.600 --> 00:04:43.120
matter. People think it's just another kind of&nbsp;
particle that only interacts via gravity and not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:48.560
the other forces. But we're still figuring that&nbsp;
out. Dark energy is quite different. Dark energy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:54.160
might be another kind of force that we'd have to&nbsp;
add to these four. Basically, at the large scale,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:54.160 --> 00:05:00.160
the universe is expanding, but not just expanding.&nbsp;
The expansion keeps speeding up, accelerating over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:04.880
time. So there must be some force or energy&nbsp;
pushing everything outwards. We don't know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:11.280
what this is, so we called it dark energy. It&nbsp;
seems like space itself has some inherent energy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:11.280 --> 00:05:15.760
which could perhaps be explained by theory of&nbsp;
quantum gravity. But we don't know that for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.760 --> 00:05:20.240
sure yet. I've made a deeper dive video all about&nbsp;
quantum gravity. If you want to find out more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:25.360
watch that. But for this video, what I really&nbsp;
want to know is if will ever be able to get to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:32.000
a theory of quantum gravity at all, because we&nbsp;
need it to explain two of the big mysteries in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:38.480
physics black holes and the Big Bang: the origin&nbsp;
of the universe. This is my map of black holes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:42.800
and basically we don't understand what's&nbsp;
going on inside them. Black holes are such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:47.600
an extreme environment in the universe that&nbsp;
gravity and quantum mechanics simply can't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:54.080
ignore each other. So to understand black holes,&nbsp;
we need to have that theory of quantum gravity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.080 --> 00:05:58.160
and for similar reasons, for the Big Bang at&nbsp;
the start of the universe, as we know it was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:04.720
like 13.8 billion years ago. The whole universe,&nbsp;
according to our best models, was squished into a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:11.680
tiny subatomic volume. So we need to have a theory&nbsp;
of quantum gravity for that original form of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.680 --> 00:06:16.720
universe as well. And here's a crazy thing&nbsp;
about the Big Bang. As the universe expanded,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:23.280
there's a point here where the matter was spread&nbsp;
out enough for light to escape and we can see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:29.440
that first light today is radio waves. It's this&nbsp;
the cosmic microwave background. And this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:35.760
furthest away thing we can ever see with light.&nbsp;
This is the entire night sky. So this covers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:41.440
every direction and these grains of color. You can&nbsp;
see this is the granularity of quantum mechanics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:46.640
frozen in time from when the universe was tiny&nbsp;
and now has been stretched out to the size of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:52.800
the observable universe. So the smallest things&nbsp;
in the universe now stretched over the biggest&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.800 --> 00:06:58.880
things in the universe. So here's the situation&nbsp;
we're in. Our theories of quantum gravity don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:04.160
work. Our best attempts like string theory&nbsp;
and loop quantum gravity, they don't give us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:09.360
any testable predictions. And this is how science&nbsp;
is supposed to work. If you've got a new theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:14.400
you need to be able to test it with a prediction.&nbsp;
And we don't have any from those theories. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:19.920
other way you can go about it is if you've got no&nbsp;
theories that are working, you need some new data,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:26.000
something that can give you a new clue about&nbsp;
what's going on. So what experiments could we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.200
do for quantum gravity? So the first option is a&nbsp;
giant particle accelerator like the one at CERN,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:36.480
but way bigger. And you build this to find out if&nbsp;
there's a quantum particle for gravity. So people&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:42.400
have hypothesized this particle. It's called a&nbsp;
graviton. And to get enough energy, you'd need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:47.920
to build a particle accelerator the size of our&nbsp;
solar system with detectors the size of Jupiter.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:53.200
And as soon as you run it, you'd create a black&nbsp;
hole. So that's not practically going to be built&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.200 --> 00:07:58.720
anytime soon. Another way you could take is to&nbsp;
try and delve down into the quantum realm and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:04.160
make incredibly sensitive measurements of gravity.&nbsp;
So there's gravity everywhere. So there should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:09.680
be gravitons everywhere. But they're incredibly&nbsp;
difficult to detect because gravity is such a weak&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:17.920
force. So one idea is to get a massive chunk of&nbsp;
metal about one ton and cool it down really cold&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.920 --> 00:08:23.680
to get rid of all the vibrational energy inside&nbsp;
it, and then wait until a graviton bumps into it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:30.080
to make it vibrate a teeny bit. So you'd need&nbsp;
a ton of metal cooled close to absolute zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:34.640
and practically this is easier than that solar&nbsp;
system sized particle accelerator. But this is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:39.760
still way beyond what we can do today, and it&nbsp;
might be physically impossible to protect this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:44.880
detector from other sources of vibrations like&nbsp;
cosmic rays or neutrinos, which might hide the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:44.880 --> 00:08:51.280
gravitons. Also, both of these approaches assume&nbsp;
that a particle of gravity exists. That's a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.280 --> 00:08:56.800
quantum way of looking at gravity, but we don't&nbsp;
know gravity works like that. It might work in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.800 --> 00:09:01.520
different way and not have particles. Currently&nbsp;
with no experiments we can run our best option&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:01.520 --> 00:09:06.960
are observations of space specifically of&nbsp;
gravitational waves. Gravitational waves&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:12.080
are ripples in space time. These were predicted&nbsp;
by the laws of general relativity and then first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:18.320
discovered in 2017. these gravitational waves&nbsp;
could be the best chance we currently have to get&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:23.520
some clue to point us towards a theory of quantum&nbsp;
gravity. We can currently detect gravitational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:28.720
waves from Earth of black hole collisions. And&nbsp;
there's a plan to make a much larger space based&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:35.280
detector called LISA. LISA is planned to launch&nbsp;
in the mid 2030s, although this date keeps getting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:42.400
pushed back. I've basically been following the&nbsp;
mission since the 1990s, but if this does launch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:48.400
within my lifetime, it should be able to detect&nbsp;
primordial gravitational waves from the Big Bang.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:53.520
These primordial gravitational waves come from&nbsp;
fractions of a second after the Big Bang. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:53.520 --> 00:09:58.320
these are the earliest signals we could get from&nbsp;
the origins of the universe. Way before the cosmic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:03.120
microwave background, which is the earliest we&nbsp;
can currently see. There might also be faint&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:09.200
signals of these primordial gravitational waves&nbsp;
in the cosmic microwave background itself. These&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:14.720
are called B-mode polarization patterns. And&nbsp;
this is the quickest route to try and see them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:19.280
There's loads of telescopes trying to measure this&nbsp;
currently. So to understand the universe, we need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:24.640
to have a theory of quantum gravity. And these are&nbsp;
our best options to try and find one. So it looks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:30.720
like it might take a while. But here's the kicker&nbsp;
even if we did have a theory of quantum gravity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:36.320
right now, there's still things about the universe&nbsp;
that we know we'll never know. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:41.680
inside black holes, we'll never know what's going&nbsp;
on inside them. We can only ever guess, because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:47.200
anything that goes into a black hole never comes&nbsp;
out. So no information can ever escape from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:52.400
inside of a black hole, so we'll never know what's&nbsp;
going on inside them. Similarly, we'll never know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:52.400 --> 00:10:57.760
what happened at the very, very early universe.&nbsp;
The origins of the Big Bang, what caused it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:02.320
anything like that. Because there's no information&nbsp;
in the universe that could tell us similarly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:10.320
beyond the observable universe. So we can see a&nbsp;
patch of the universe, which is, 48 billion light&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:16.240
years in radius. Beyond that, we don't know what's&nbsp;
happening there. Physics could be different,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:23.040
or it could be full of anti-matter or whatever.&nbsp;
We'll never know. So unfortunately, the conclusion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:30.400
of this video is we will never fully understand&nbsp;
the universe. And so as a physicist, that's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:30.400 --> 00:11:38.240
bit sad because our knowledge, could never be&nbsp;
complete. But isn't it incredible that we can even&nbsp;&nbsp;

